description: From (the participle stem of) Late Latin *originare (“to begin, give rise to”), from Latin orīgō (“origin”).

verbs.description: originate (third-person singular simple present originates, present participle originating, simple past and past participle originated)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To cause (someone or something) to be; to bring (someone or something) into existence; to produce or initiate a person or thing. [from 17th c.]
examples: For the first time since Douglas Fairbanks Sr. originated the role in the 1920 silent "The Mark of Zorro," the hero will be played by a Hispanic actor.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To come into existence; to have origin or beginning; to spring, be derived (from, with). [from 18th c.]
examples: The scheme originated with the governor and council.
